      The PSUS thesis
   =20
 =20
If you are a US equity fund manager, your job is to buy stocks listed in th=
e US. Which stocks should you buy? Well, stocks you think will go up, good =
companies, companies with good managers and good businesses,=C2=A0that sort=
 of thing.Here=E2=80=99s a stock called SPY. It was up 24% last year; it ha=
d a rough 2022, but it was up double digits each of the three previous year=
s and has a long track record of pretty good returns. Should you buy it? Pr=
obably not, no. SPY is the SPDR S&P 500 ETF Trust, an exchange-traded fund =
that owns the stocks in the S&P 500 stock index. Your job, as a fund manage=
r, is to pick good stocks, not to just buy someone else=E2=80=99s index fun=
d.Here=E2=80=99s a stock called ARKK. It was up 68% last year but it=E2=80=
=99s down this year; maybe it=E2=80=99ll come back. Should you buy it? Agai=
n, seems a bit iffy: ARKK is the ARK Innovation ETF, an exchange-traded fun=
d managed by celebrity investment manager Cathie Wood. Again, your job is t=
o pick good stocks, not to outsource the picking to Cathie Wood (and pay he=
r fees). Also ARKK=E2=80=99s portfolio is public! You can buy the stocks yo=
urself; you won=E2=80=99t get quite Wood=E2=80=99s results but you won=E2=
=80=99t pay her fees either. And in fact Bloomberg=E2=80=99s list of ARKK=
=E2=80=99s holders is not heavy on traditional asset managers: The Fidelity=
s and Capitals and BlackRocks of the world do not seem to be big holders of=
 ARKK.=C2=A0Here=E2=80=99s a stock called BRK/A. It has had a pretty succes=
sful run over a long period. BRK/A is Berkshire Hathaway Inc. It is =E2=80=
=A6=C2=A0I mean, I suppose it was originally a textile company, and now it =
is a conglomerate that does a lot of insurance, but in some loose sense it =
is Warren Buffett=E2=80=99s vehicle for buying public stocks and also whole=
 companies. Roughly 30% of its assets consist of investments in equity secu=
rities; more than 10% of its market capitalization is made up=C2=A0just=C2=
=A0of its stake in Apple Inc. Should you buy BRK/A? Again, your job is to p=
ick good stocks, not to outsource the picking to Warren Buffett and his lie=
utenants, but =E2=80=A6. it is Warren Buffett? It=E2=80=99s not=C2=A0litera=
lly=C2=A0an investment fund? It=E2=80=99s a big conglomerate with a lot of =
insurance operations. And when he buys stocks they tend to go up. Maybe it=
=E2=80=99s fine. BRK/A=E2=80=99s second-biggest holder is Fidelity.=C2=A0He=
re=E2=80=99s a stock called EQR. EQR is Equity Residential, and it is an in=
vestment fund, a real estate investment trust (REIT), a fund that buys apar=
tment buildings and manage them on behalf of investors. In some loose sense=
 REITs =E2=80=9Care similar to mutual funds,=E2=80=9D says Investopedia,=C2=
=A0=E2=80=9Cin that REITs pool together capital from a large number of inve=
stors.=E2=80=9D Nobody especially thinks of large public equity REITs that =
way these days, I don=E2=80=99t think. EQR is plainly a=C2=A0company, one w=
hose operations include buying and developing and managing apartment buildi=
ngs. If you are an equity fund manager, sure, go ahead, buy EQR. It is a st=
ock that can give you exposure to apartment buildings; you are allowed to b=
uy stocks but not apartment buildings. EQR=E2=80=99s big holders include T.=
 Rowe Price and Fidelity, but its biggest holders are Vanguard Group and Bl=
ackRock Inc., because it is a large and normal enough stock that it is in t=
he S&P 500 index.Here=E2=80=99s a stock called PSUS. The Financial Times re=
ports:Bill Ackman has told potential investors in the US-based investment f=
und he is working to take public that his prolific social media presence wi=
ll help the vehicle trade at a premium valuation.The billionaire hedge fund=
 manager is soliciting investments for a listed fund of up to $25bn called =
Pershing Square USA, which if successful, would make it one of the largest =
initial public offerings of all time, rivalling oil major Saudi Aramco and =
Chinese tech group Alibaba. =E2=80=A6The new fund will be structured as a m=
anagement company listed on the New York Stock Exchange and will invest in =
large, publicly traded companies with competitive advantages that Ackman be=
lieves are undervalued. While the stock will be easily tradable, the fund w=
ill have a closed-end structure, meaning its assets cannot be redeemed, unl=
ike a traditional mutual fund, allowing for a longer-term investing style. =
=E2=80=A6=C2=A0Ackman is also comparing the vehicle to an ordinary corporat=
ion and believes it could eventually be included in broad stock market indi=
ces. =E2=80=9CThis isn=E2=80=99t a closed-end fund, this is Bill Ackman Inc=
orporated,=E2=80=9D said the investor.We have talked a number of times abou=
t PSUS, but here I want to point out that there are two very ambitious elem=
ents to Ackman=E2=80=99s pitch,=C2=A0size=C2=A0and=C2=A0price: He wants to =
raise $25 billion, and he wants the fund to trade at a premium to its net a=
sset value.=C2=A0Trading at a premium=C2=A0is ambitious, because PSUS will =
consist mostly of a smallish, low-turnover=C2=A0portfolio of large listed s=
tocks, a portfolio that will be disclosed periodically (and that Ackman wil=
l tweet about). If you want to buy the dozen or so stocks that PSUS will ho=
ld, you can do that yourself. Paying Bill Ackman $60 to buy $50 worth of st=
ocks seems like a worse trade than just buying the $50 of stocks yourself.A=
lso, Ackman already has a listed closed-end fund=C2=A0in Europe, Pershing S=
quare Holdings, which he can=E2=80=99t tweet about and which has some disad=
vantages for US investors. It trades at about a 20% discount to net asset v=
alue. So (1) precedent suggests PSUS will trade at a discount and (2) you m=
ight be able to more or less replicate its portfolio by=C2=A0buying PSH at =
a discount, rather than buying its stocks at net asset value.There are a fe=
w responses to this:=09Ackman has a good track record of picking stocks, an=
d presumably he=E2=80=99ll build his positions before disclosing them. When=
 he discloses them, they will go up,=C2=A0because of his large social media=
 following and/or because of his track record of picking good stocks. This =
will benefit holders of PSUS (which will buy the stocks before he tweets) b=
ut not copycats (who will only buy the stocks after he tweets). Therefore, =
PSUS will outperform a copycat portfolio, so it should trade at a premium t=
o NAV.=09PSUS will not=C2=A0just be=C2=A0a portfolio of stocks: It also =E2=
=80=9Cseeks to opportunistically utilize asymmetric hedges to protect its i=
nvestment portfolio against specific macroeconomic risks, and to capitalize=
 on market volatility,=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cto structure these asymmetric =
hedges using derivative instruments where the amount of capital at risk is =
finite (an amount which is expected to typically represent a small, single-=
digit percentage of the Company=E2=80=99s total assets), with the potential=
 to earn large multiples of the invested capital if the identified risk or =
macro event occurs.=E2=80=9D Ackman has had some big wins with trades like =
this =E2=80=94=C2=A0notably a cheap but lucrative=C2=A0bet against credit j=
ust before Covid-19 hit =E2=80=94=C2=A0and they are much of what you pay fo=
r if you hire him as your hedge fund manager.=09Ackman is good at social me=
dia and has a large retail following, and if there is one single most impor=
tant lesson from the last few years in financial markets, it is that stocks=
 with large retail followings on social media can sustainably trade at a la=
rge premium to their intrinsic value.That last point is the most obvious on=
e. =E2=80=9CThere is a meme-stock element to all of this,=E2=80=9D I wrote =
last month, and the Financial Times says
  [1]
:Ackman referred to his social media following and heavy media coverage as =
=E2=80=9Cnotoriety=E2=80=9D in the presentation. =E2=80=9CI have built up a=
 large base of institutional and retail followers that follow our every mov=
e=E2=80=89.=E2=80=89.=E2=80=89.=E2=80=89Media interest is valuable in attra=
cting investor interest and also in creating liquidity for our shareholders=
,=E2=80=9D he said.Pershing Square USA is registered as a so-called 40 Act =
fund, which carries fewer regulatory restrictions on communications than Pe=
rshing Square Holdings.=E2=80=9CThe fund is just geared to retail,=E2=80=9D=
 said one investment manager who has spoken with Ackman. =E2=80=9CHe can ha=
ve direct engagement in the US, that=E2=80=99s why he thinks it will trade =
up. He wasn=E2=80=99t allowed to tweet about his London-listed fund,=E2=80=
=9D added the investor.But Ackman=E2=80=99s=C2=A0size=C2=A0goals are also a=
mbitious: A=C2=A0$25 billion initial public offering is really big, probabl=
y too big for a fund =E2=80=9Cjust geared to retail.=E2=80=9D There are sto=
cks that have way more intense=C2=A0retail attention =E2=80=94=C2=A0think G=
ameStop Corp. or Trump Media & Technology Group =E2=80=94=C2=A0with much sm=
aller market caps than $25 billion.=C2=A0So there is a pitch to=C2=A0instit=
utional stock=C2=A0investors, to asset managers, which is in part, sure, =
=E2=80=9Cthis might trade at a premium because retail investors love me,=E2=
=80=9D but which is also in part =E2=80=9Cthis is not a stock fund.=E2=80=
=9D If you are an institutional stock investor, buying a stock that is=C2=
=A0just another stock investor=E2=80=99s fund=C2=A0is a weird move: You=E2=
=80=99re paying extra fees, and you=E2=80=99re outsourcing the work of stoc=
k-picking to him. But buying a stock that=C2=A0is a company =E2=80=94=C2=A0=
that happens to be a company that invests mostly in stocks =E2=80=94=C2=A0i=
s fine. Investing in Berkshire Hathaway is more socially acceptable than in=
vesting in ARKK.I should say that there are also=C2=A0legal=C2=A0limits on =
mutual funds investing in other mutual funds: Generally you can=E2=80=99t h=
ave more than 10% of your fund in other registered funds, or more than 5% i=
n any one registered fund. This does not restrict mutual funds from investi=
ng in Berkshire Hathaway (not a registered investment company), though it w=
ould limit their=C2=A0investments=C2=A0in PSUS. On the other hand, unlike B=
erkshire Hathaway, PSUS does not pay corporate taxes. That=E2=80=99s right =
in the tagline: =E2=80=9CPSUS is an Investment Holding Company That Pays No=
 Corporate Tax=E2=80=9D is the description on slide 8 of the investor prese=
ntation.=C2=A0Also, on slide 15 of that presentation: =E2=80=9CExpected res=
earch analyst coverage & index inclusion.=E2=80=9D If PSUS is in the indexe=
s, then index funds will buy it. Stock=C2=A0funds are not generally in the =
big stock indexes (that would be weird!
  [2]
), but REITs can be, and Berkshire Hathaway is. S&P Dow Jones Indices publi=
shes its index methodology, which says that =E2=80=9Ccorporations (includin=
g equity and mortgage REITs)=E2=80=9D are eligible but =E2=80=9Cclosed-end =
funds=E2=80=9D are not. Maybe PSUS isn=E2=80=99t a closed-end fund, though?=
 It=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Can Investment Holding Company That Pays No Corporate=
 Tax.=E2=80=9D Or rather: =E2=80=9CThis isn=E2=80=99t a closed-end fund, th=
is is Bill Ackman Incorporated.=E2=80=9D
