</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you are a US equity fund manager, y=
our job is to buy stocks listed in the US. Which stocks should you buy? Wel=
l, stocks you think will go up, good companies, companies with good manager=
s and good businesses,=C2=A0that sort of thing.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px=
 0;">Here=E2=80=99s a stock called SPY. It was up 24% last year; it had a r=
ough 2022, but it was up double digits each of the three previous years and=
 has a long track record of pretty good returns. Should you buy it? Probabl=
y not, no. SPY is the SPDR S&amp;P 500 ETF Trust, an exchange-traded fund t=
hat owns the stocks in the S&amp;P 500 stock index. Your job, as a fund man=
ager, is to pick good stocks, not to just buy someone else=E2=80=99s index =
fund.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here=E2=80=99s a stock called ARKK. I=
t was up 68% last year but it=E2=80=99s down this year; maybe it=E2=80=99ll=
 come back. Should you buy it? Again, seems a bit iffy: ARKK is the ARK Inn=
ovation ETF, an exchange-traded fund managed by celebrity investment manage=
r Cathie Wood. Again, your job is to pick good stocks, not to outsource the=
 picking to Cathie Wood (and pay her fees). Also ARKK=E2=80=99s portfolio i=
s public! You can buy the stocks yourself; you won=E2=80=99t get quite Wood=
=E2=80=99s results but you won=E2=80=99t pay her fees either. And in fact B=
loomberg=E2=80=99s list of ARKK=E2=80=99s holders is not heavy on tradition=
al asset managers: The Fidelitys and Capitals and BlackRocks of the world d=
o not seem to be big holders of ARKK.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"=
>Here=E2=80=99s a stock called BRK/A. It has had a pretty successful run ov=
er a long period. BRK/A is Berkshire Hathaway Inc. It is =E2=80=A6=C2=A0I m=
ean, I suppose it was originally a <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbu=
siness.com/click/36079366.196399/aHR0cHM6Ly9lbi53aWtpcGVkaWEub3JnL3dpa2kvQm=
Vya3NoaXJlX0hhdGhhd2F5/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB5d18724f" itemprop=3D"Story=
Link" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; te=
xt-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-col=
or: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">textile c=
ompany</a>, and now it is a conglomerate that does a lot of insurance, but =
in some loose sense it is Warren Buffett=E2=80=99s vehicle for buying publi=
c stocks and also whole companies. Roughly 30% of its assets consist of inv=
estments in equity securities; more than 10% of its market capitalization i=
s made up=C2=A0<em>just=C2=A0</em>of its stake in Apple Inc. Should you buy=
 BRK/A? Again, your job is to pick good stocks, not to outsource the pickin=
g to Warren Buffett and his lieutenants, but =E2=80=A6. it is Warren Buffet=
t? It=E2=80=99s not=C2=A0<em>literally=C2=A0</em>an investment fund? It=E2=
=80=99s a big conglomerate with a lot of insurance operations. And when he =
buys stocks they tend to go up. Maybe it=E2=80=99s fine. BRK/A=E2=80=99s se=
cond-biggest holder is Fidelity.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here=
=E2=80=99s a stock called EQR. EQR is Equity Residential, and it is an inve=
stment fund, a real estate investment trust (REIT), a fund that buys apartm=
ent buildings and manage them on behalf of investors. In some loose sense R=
EITs =E2=80=9Care similar to mutual funds,=E2=80=9D <a href=3D"https://link=
.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/36079366.196399/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuaW52ZXN0b=
3BlZGlhLmNvbS9hcnRpY2xlcy9wZi8wOC9yZWl0LXRheC5hc3A/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23c=
