arget=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important;=
 border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-styl=
e: solid; background-color: #ccc;">smallish, low-turnover=C2=A0portfolio</a=
> of large listed stocks, a portfolio that will be disclosed periodically (=
and that Ackman will tweet about). If you want to buy the dozen or so stock=
s that PSUS will hold, you can do that yourself. Paying Bill Ackman $60 to =
buy $50 worth of stocks seems like a worse trade than just buying the $50 o=
f stocks yourself.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also, Ackman already has=
 a listed closed-end fund=C2=A0in Europe, Pershing Square Holdings, which h=
e can=E2=80=99t tweet about and which has some disadvantages for US investo=
rs. It trades at about a 20% discount to net asset value. So (1) precedent =
suggests PSUS will trade at a discount and (2) you might be able to more or=
 less replicate its portfolio by=C2=A0<em>buying PSH at a discount</em>, ra=
ther than buying its stocks at net asset value.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px=
 0;">There are a few responses to this:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: de=
cimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: =
5px;">Ackman has a good track record of picking stocks, and presumably he=
=E2=80=99ll build his positions before disclosing them. When he discloses t=
hem, they will go up,=C2=A0because of his large social media following and/=
or because of his track record of picking good stocks. This will benefit ho=
lders of PSUS (which will buy the stocks before he tweets) but not copycats=
 (who will only buy the stocks after he tweets). Therefore, PSUS will outpe=
rform a copycat portfolio, so it should trade at a premium to NAV.</li>=09<=
li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">PSUS will not=C2=A0<em>just </em>be=C2=A0a=
 portfolio of stocks: <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/cl=
ick/36079366.196399/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzI=
wMDI2NjAvMDAwMTE5MzEyNTI0MTc2NTQxL2Q2MjM3ODFkbjJhLmh0bQ/607f07ceef4b8524a31=
9a23cBa2c022ba" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_b=
lank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bot=
tom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; b=
ackground-color: #ccc;">It also</a> =E2=80=9Cseeks to opportunistically uti=
lize asymmetric hedges to protect its investment portfolio against specific=
 macroeconomic risks, and to capitalize on market volatility,=E2=80=9D and =
=E2=80=9Cto structure these asymmetric hedges using derivative instruments =
where the amount of capital at risk is finite (an amount which is expected =
to typically represent a small, single-digit percentage of the Company=E2=
=80=99s total assets), with the potential to earn large multiples of the in=
vested capital if the identified risk or macro event occurs.=E2=80=9D Ackma=
n has had some big wins with trades like this =E2=80=94=C2=A0notably a <a h=
ref=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/36079366.196399/aHR0cH=
M6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjAtMDMtMjcvZXZlcnlvb=
