om: 5px;">The bank pays you a little interest each month, and lets you take=
 out your money (or put more back in) at any time.</li></ol><p style=3D"mar=
gin: 16px 0;">Just a different trade. Nothing wrong with it, but different.=
</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On first principles, if you were trying to=
 set up a financial system, which of these things would you pair with each =
other? Like: There are people who need to borrow money to buy houses. They=
=E2=80=99ll need the money for decades, and they=E2=80=99ll make monthly pa=
yments to amortize the loans. And there are=C2=A0people who need to fund th=
eir retirement, who=E2=80=99ll sock away a lot of money at the start of ret=
irement so they can get monthly payments for decades. And then there are so=
me other people who need access to liquid cash, so they=E2=80=99ll put away=
 some money that they might need at any moment. Which source of money =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0the people who need to put away money for decades in exchange f=
or fixed payments, or the people who need to put away money to pay rent nex=
t week =E2=80=94=C2=A0should provide the funding for the people who need lo=
ans?</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Historically the answer is =E2=80=9Cth=
